entry.title: Remove primordial SiteInstance from extensions' ProcessManager.
entry.content:
The ProcessManager in the extensions code maintains a primordial SiteInstance in its site_instance_ member. Historically it was necessary in order to implement process model semantics required by extensions. However, at this point, the process model for extensions isolates them all from each other and this initial SiteInstance is no longer necessary.
This issues is filed to track the work necessary to remove this member, which is non-trivial change and will land across multiple CLs.

entry.title: WebNN: Use LOG(ERROR) in DirectML backend
entry.content: For general errors returned from D3D like device removed and unanticipated ones, use LOG(ERROR) in DirectML backend, so users can view them in the about://gpu log messages.

entry.title: Roll libjpeg_turbo
entry.content:
libjpeg_turbo upstream is on 3.0.2; our repo is at 2.1.5.1, which is more than a year old.
The newer version contains speedups, security fixes, and API improvements. I don't know what (if anything) we've backported, or if the API changes will be onerous for us.

entry.title: Live region changed event should not be fired on the creation of a live region node
entry.content:
With IA2, we only fire a live region when the live region node's content changes. With UIA, we're also firing a live region when the node gets created. This leads to unexpected behaviors with NVDA and JAWS when UIA is enabled.
We're in the process of fixing that difference so that with UIA too with only fire live region events when the content changes.

entry.title: Show human-readable build number on build page when URL only includes build ID
entry.content:
eg: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Builder/b8750557649975428929/infra
Some services link to bb builds like the above (with the build ID in the URL). For most/all chrome builders, we enable "build numbers" which are easier on the eyes.
For the build link above, its corresponding build number is `184349`: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Builder/184349/infra
Such URLs are generally easier to use that build ID ones. eg: You can compare two URLs and immediately roughly know how far apart the two builds are. You can also manually bisect very easily by tweaking the build number.
But mapping to build number when all you have is the build ID is not easy. So can we get the build number displayed somewhere (like in the infra tab) in URLs like https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Builder/b8750557649975428929/infra

entry.title: owner cleans up job can suggest to use primary email if secondary email is used in OWNERS
entry.content:
In b/333717295, user is reporting that if the secondary email is listed in OWNERS file, that email may not show up in the find owner suggestion because most of the Gerrit users doesn't have permission to view secondary email of a given user.
To mitigate this issue, a long term solution could be to extend our [owners clean up infrastructure](http://go/chrome-owners-cleanup-docs) so that it can propose a CL to replace the secondary email with the primary email if a secondary email is detected in the OWNERS file.

entry.title: $0 - $4 do not play nice with pseudo elements
entry.content:
1. Inspect an element that has a pseudo element, e.g. one of the scrollers on https://scroll-driven-animations.style/demos/scroll-shadows/css/ 2. Select the ::before or ::after pseudo from that scroller in the Elements panel 3. Print $0 via the console
$0 holds a reference the actual element that contains the pseudo, not the pseudo itself.
While I know you can’t querySelector a pseudo element, sometimes it’s necessary to also know if a pseudo was selected or not instead of getting back the reference to the element. For example, when trying to extract the animations that are applied to the selected pseudo – https://github.com/bramus/scroll-driven-animations-debugger-extension/issues/24
There would need to be a way to know if and which pseudo was selected, in addition to $0.
(Also pretty confusing that DevTools shows “== $0” next to the selected pseudo, which is not true)
